# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: antisense-oligonucleotides
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/antisense-therapy] The common stem for antisense oligonucleotides drugs is -rsen.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/antisense-therapy] The substem -virsen designates antiviral antisense oligonucleotides.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/antisense-therapy] Developments in ASO modification are separated into three generations.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/antisense-therapy] Generation one is called backbone-modified and focuses on the phosphodiester group of the nucleotide.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/antisense-therapy] These modifications led to better distribution, reduced urinary excretion, and prolonged residence time of the ASOs in the cell.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/antisense-therapy] Some examples of first generation modifications include the addition of a phosphorothioate group (PS), methyl group, or nitrogen.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/antisense-therapy] The most common is the phosphorothioate group (PS) in which the oxygen atoms of a phosphodiester group are replaced with sulfur atoms, greatly improving efficacy and reducing degradation.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/antisense-therapy] Generation two is sugar-modified, focused on the ribose sugar of the nucleotide.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/antisense-therapy] This generation saw improved binding affinity while reducing degradation.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/antisense-therapy] Some examples of generation two modifications are the substitution of R group with morpholine group (MO) and the usage of phosphorodiamidate morpholino oligomer (PMO) and thiomorpholine oligomer (TMO) as linkages between the ribose sugar and phosphodiester group in the backbone.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/antisense-therapy] Generation three is nucleobase-modified, the least common type of modification.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/antisense-therapy] These modifications enhanced binding affinity and cell penetration while reducing degradation and off-target effects.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/antisense-therapy] Examples include the introduction of G-clamps, pseudoisocytosine, and the substitution of bases with amine, thione, halogen, alkyl, alkenyl, or alkynyl groups.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/antisense-therapy] ASO-based drugs employ highly modified, single-stranded chains of synthetic nucleic acids that achieve wide tissue distribution with very long half-lives.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/antisense-therapy] For instance, many ASO-based drugs contain phosphorothioate substitutions and 2' sugar modifications to inhibit nuclease degradation enabling vehicle-free delivery to cells.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/antisense-therapy] Phosphorothioate ASOs can be delivered to cells without the need of a delivery vehicle.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/antisense-therapy] ASOs do not penetrate the blood brain barrier when delivered systemically but they can distribute across the neuraxis if injected in the cerebrospinal fluid typically by intrathecal administration.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/antisense-therapy] Newer formulations using conjugated ligands greatly enhances delivery efficiency and cell-type specific targeting.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/antisense-therapy] Tofersen (marketed as Qalsody) was approved by the FDA for the treatment of SOD1- associated amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (ALS) in 2023.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/antisense-therapy] It was developed by Biogen under a licensing agreement with Ionis Pharmaceuticals.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/antisense-therapy] In trials the drug was found to lower levels of an ALS biomarker, neurofilament light change, and in long-term trial extensions to slow disease.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/antisense-therapy] Under the terms of the FDA's accelerated approval program, a confirmatory study will be conducted in presymptomatic gene carriers to provide additional evidence.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/antisense-therapy] Milasen is a novel individualized therapeutic agent that was designed and approved by the FDA for the treatment of Batten disease.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/antisense-therapy] This therapy serves as an example of personalized medicine.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/antisense-therapy] In 2019, a report was published detailing the development of milasen, an antisense oligonucleotide drug for Batten disease, under an expanded-access investigational clinical protocol authorized by the Food and Drug Administration (FDA).
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/antisense-therapy] Milasen "itself remains an investigational drug, and it is not suited for the treatment of other patients with Batten's disease" because it was customized for a single patient's specific mutation.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/antisense-therapy] However it is an example of individualized genomic medicine therapeutical intervention.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/antisense-therapy] Fomivirsen (marketed as Vitravene), was approved by the U.S.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/antisense-therapy] FDA in August 1998, as a treatment for cytomegalovirus retinitis.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/antisense-therapy] Several morpholino oligos have been approved to treat specific groups of mutations causing Duchenne muscular dystrophy.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/antisense-therapy] In September 2016, eteplirsen (ExonDys51) received FDA approval for the treatment of cases that can benefit from skipping exon 51 of the dystrophin transcript.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/antisense-therapy] In December 2019, golodirsen (Vyondys 53) received FDA approval for the treatment of cases that can benefit from skipping exon 53 of the dystrophin transcript.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/antisense-therapy] In August 2020, viltolarsen (Viltepso) received FDA approval for the treatment of cases that can benefit from skipping exon 53 of the dystrophin transcript.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/antisense-therapy] A companion human translational study by Golinski et al. investigated the developmental biology and preclinical feasibility of *KCNT1* knockdown in utero.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/antisense-therapy] Volanesorsen was approved by the European Medicines Agency (EMA) for the treatment of familial chylomicronaemia syndrome in May 2019.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/antisense-therapy] In January 2013 mipomersen (marketed as Kynamro) was approved by the FDA for the treatment of homozygous familial hypercholesterolemia.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/antisense-therapy] Inotersen received FDA approval for the treatment of hereditary transthyretin-mediated amyloidosis in October 2018.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/antisense-therapy] The application for inotersen was granted orphan drug designation.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/antisense-therapy] It was developed by Ionis Pharmaceuticals and licensed to Akcea Therapeutics.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/antisense-therapy] Patisiran (sold under Onpattro) was developed by Alnylam Pharmaceuticals, and also approved for use in the US and EU in 2018 with orphan drug designation.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/antisense-therapy] Its mechanism-of-action is the active substance of small interfering RNA (siRNA), which allows it to interfere with and block the production of transthyretin.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/antisense-therapy] As such, it was the first FDA-approved siRNA therapeutic.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/antisense-therapy] In 2004, development of an antisense therapy for spinal muscular atrophy began.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/antisense-therapy] Over the following years, an antisense oligonucleotide later named nusinersen was developed by Ionis Pharmaceuticals under a licensing agreement with Biogen.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/antisense-therapy] In December 2016, nusinersen received regulatory approval from FDA and soon after, from other regulatory agencies worldwide.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/antisense-therapy] As of 2020, more than 50 antisense oligonucleotides were in clinical trials, including over 25 in advanced clinical trials (phase II or III).
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/antisense-therapy] A follow-on drug to Inotersen is being developed by Ionis Pharmaceuticals and under license to Akcea Therapeutics for hereditary transthyretin-mediated amyloidosis.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/antisense-therapy] In this formulation the ASO is conjugated to N-Acetylgalactosamine enabling hepatocyte-specific delivery, greatly reducing dose requirements and side effect profile while increasing the level of transthyretin reduction in patients.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/antisense-therapy] Tominersen (also known as IONIS-HTTRx and RG6042) was tested in a phase 3 trial for Huntington's disease although this trial was discontinued on March 21, 2021, due to lack of efficacy.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/antisense-therapy] It is currently licensed to Roche by Ionis Pharmaceuticals.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] A **Morpholino**, also known as a **phosphorodiamidate Morpholino oligomer** (**PMO**), is a nucleic acid analog whose backbone consists of methylenemorpholine rings linked through phosphorodiamidate groups, in contrast to the sugars linked through phosphates found in natural nucleic acids.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] Synthetic oligomers of Morpholinos are used in molecular biology to modify gene expression.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] Morpholinos block access of other molecules to small (~25 base) specific sequences of the base-pairing surfaces of ribonucleic acid (RNA).
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] Morpholinos are used as research tools for reverse genetics by knocking down gene function.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] Morpholinos are in development as pharmaceutical therapeutics targeted against pathogenic organisms such as bacteria or viruses and genetic diseases.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] A Morpholino-based drug eteplirsen from Sarepta Therapeutics received accelerated approval from the US Food and Drug Administration in September 2016 for the treatment of some mutations causing Duchenne muscular dystrophy, although the approval process was mired in controversy.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] Other Morpholino-based drugs golodirsen, viltolarsen, and casimersen (also for Duchenne muscular dystrophy) were approved by the FDA in 2019–2021.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] "Morpholino" is often capitalized to distinguish the nucleic acid type from other chemicals containing a six-membered morpholine ring, but this usage is not consistent across scientific literature.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] Vivo-Morpholinos and PPMO are modified forms of Morpholinos with chemical groups covalently attached to facilitate entry into cells.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] Morpholino oligos were conceived by Summerton (Gene Tools) at AntiVirals Inc.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] (now Sarepta Therapeutics) and originally developed in collaboration with Weller.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] Morpholinos are synthetic molecules that are the product of a redesign of natural nucleic acid structure.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] Usually 25 bases in length, they bind to complementary sequences of RNA or single-stranded DNA by standard nucleic acid base-pairing.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] In terms of structure, the difference between Morpholinos and DNA is that, while Morpholinos have standard nucleic acid bases, those bases are bound to methylenemorpholine rings linked through phosphorodiamidate groups instead of phosphates.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] The figure compares the structures of the two strands depicted there, one of RNA and the other of a Morpholino.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] Replacement of anionic phosphates with the uncharged phosphorodiamidate groups eliminates ionization in the usual physiological pH range, so Morpholinos in organisms or cells are uncharged molecules.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] The entire backbone of a Morpholino is made from these modified subunits.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] Morpholinos do not trigger the degradation of their target RNA molecules, unlike many antisense structural types (e.g., phosphorothioates, siRNA).
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] Instead, Morpholinos act by "steric blocking", binding to a target sequence within an RNA, inhibiting molecules that might otherwise interact with the RNA.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] Morpholino oligos are often used to investigate the role of a specific mRNA transcript in an embryo.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] Developmental biologists inject Morpholino oligos into eggs or embryos of zebrafish, African clawed frog (*Xenopus*), sea urchin and killifish (*F. heteroclitus*) producing morphant embryos, or electroporate Morpholinos into chick embryos at later development stages.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] With appropriate cytosolic delivery systems, Morpholinos are effective in cell culture.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] Vivo-Morpholinos, in which the oligo is covalently linked to a delivery dendrimer, enter cells when administered systemically in adult animals or in tissue cultures.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] Gene knockdown is achieved by reducing the expression of a particular gene in a cell.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] In the case of protein-coding genes, this usually leads to a reduction in the quantity of the corresponding protein in the cell.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] These molecules have been applied to studies in several model organisms, including mice, zebrafish, frogs and sea urchins.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] Morpholinos can also modify the splicing of pre-mRNA or inhibit the maturation and activity of miRNA.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] Techniques for targeting Morpholinos to RNAs and delivering Morpholinos into cells have recently been reviewed in a journal article and in book form.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] In eukaryotic organisms, pre-mRNA is transcribed in the nucleus, introns are spliced out, then the mature mRNA is exported from the nucleus to the cytoplasm.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] The small subunit of the ribosome usually starts by binding at the 5' end of the mRNA and is joined there by various other eukaryotic initiation factors, forming the initiation complex.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] The initiation complex scans along the mRNA strand until it reaches a start codon, and then the large subunit of the ribosome attaches to the small subunit and translation of a protein begins.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] This entire process is referred to as gene expression; it is the process by which the information in a gene, encoded as a sequence of bases in DNA, is converted into the structure of a protein.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] A Morpholino can modify splicing, block translation, or block other functional sites on RNA depending on the Morpholino's base sequence.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] Bound to the 5'-untranslated region of messenger RNA (mRNA), Morpholinos can interfere with progression of the ribosomal initiation complex from the 5' cap to the start codon.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] This prevents translation of the coding region of the targeted transcript (called "knocking down" gene expression).
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] This is useful experimentally when an investigator wishes to know the function of a particular protein; Morpholinos provide a convenient means of knocking down expression of the protein and learning how that knockdown changes the cells or organism.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] Some Morpholinos knock down expression so effectively that, after degradation of preexisting proteins, the targeted proteins become undetectable by Western blot.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] In 2016 a synthetic peptide-conjugated PMO (PPMO) was found to inhibit the expression of New Delhi Metallo-beta-lactamase, an enzyme that many drug-resistant bacteria use to destroy carbapenems.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] Preventing the binding of snRNP U1 (at the donor site) or U2/U5 (at the polypyrimidine moiety and acceptor site) can cause modified splicing, commonly excluding exons from the mature mRNA.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] Targeting some splice targets results in intron inclusions, while activation of cryptic splice sites can lead to partial inclusions or exclusions.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] Targets of U11/U12 snRNPs can also be blocked.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] Splice modification can be conveniently assayed by reverse-transcriptase polymerase chain reaction (RT-PCR) and is seen as a band shift after gel electrophoresis of RT-PCR products.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] Morpholinos have been used to block miRNA activity and maturation.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] Fluorescein-tagged Morpholinos combined with fluorescein-specific antibodies can be used as probes for in-situ hybridization to miRNAs.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] Morpholinos can block ribozyme activity.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] U2 and U12 snRNP functions have been inhibited by Morpholinos.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] Morpholinos targeted to "slippery" mRNA sequences within protein coding regions can induce translational frameshifts.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] Morpholinos can block RNA editing, poly(A) tailing and translocation sequences.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] Morpholino activities against this variety of targets suggest that Morpholinos can be used as a general-purpose tool for blocking interactions of proteins or nucleic acids with mRNA.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] Morpholinos have become a standard knockdown tool in animal embryonic systems, which have a broader range of gene expression than adult cells and can be strongly affected by an off-target interaction.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] Following initial injections into frog or fish embryos at the single-cell or few-cell stages, Morpholino effects can be measured up to five days later, after most of the processes of organogenesis and differentiation are past, with observed phenotypes consistent with target-gene knockdown.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] Control oligos with irrelevant sequences usually produce no change in embryonic phenotype, evidence of the Morpholino oligo's sequence-specificity and lack of non-antisense effects.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] The dose required for a knockdown can be reduced by coinjection of several Morpholino oligos targeting the same mRNA, which is an effective strategy for reducing or eliminating dose-dependent off-target RNA interactions.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] mRNA rescue experiments can sometimes restore the wild-type phenotype to the embryos and provide evidence for the specificity of a Morpholino.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] In an mRNA rescue, a Morpholino is co-injected with an mRNA that codes for the morphlino's protein.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] However, the rescue mRNA has a modified 5'-UTR (untranslated region) so that the rescue mRNA contains no target for the Morpholino.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] The rescue mRNA's coding region encodes the protein of interest.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] Translation of the rescue mRNA replaces production of the protein that was knocked down by the Morpholino.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] Since the rescue mRNA would not affect phenotypic changes due to the Morpholino's off-target gene expression modulation, this return to wild-type phenotype is further evidence of Morpholino specificity.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] In some cases, ectopic expression of the rescue RNA makes recovery of the wild-type phenotype impossible.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] In embryos, Morpholinos can be tested in null mutants to check for unexpected RNA interactions, then used in a wild-type embryo to reveal the acute knockdown phenotype.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] The knockdown phenotype is often more extreme than the mutant phenotype; in the mutant, effects of losing the null gene can be concealed by genetic compensation.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] Because of their completely unnatural backbones, Morpholinos are not recognized by cellular proteins.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] Nucleases do not degrade Morpholinos, nor are they degraded in serum or in cells.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] Up to 18% of Morpholinos appear to induce nontarget-related phenotypes including cell death in the central nervous system and somite tissues of zebrafish embryos.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] Most of these effects are due to activation of p53-mediated apoptosis and can be suppressed by co-injection of an anti-p53 Morpholino along with the experimental Morpholino.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] Moreover, the p53-mediated apoptotic effect of a Morpholino knockdown has been phenocopied using another antisense structural type, showing the p53-mediated apoptosis to be a consequence of the loss of the targeted protein and not a consequence of the knockdown oligo type.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] It appears that these effects are sequence-specific; as in most cases, if a Morpholino is associated with non-target effects, the 4-base mismatch Morpholino will not trigger these effects.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] A cause for concern in the use of Morpholinos is the potential for "off-target" effects.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] Whether an observed morphant phenotype is due to the intended knockdown or an interaction with an off-target RNA can often be addressed in embryos by running another experiment to confirm that the observed morphant phenotype results from the knockdown of the expected target.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] As mentioned above, rescue of observed phenotypes by coinjecting a rescue mRNA is, when feasible, a reliable test of specificity of a Morpholino.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] For a Morpholino to be effective, it must be delivered past the cell membrane into the cytosol of a cell.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] Once in the cytosol, Morpholinos freely diffuse between the cytosol and nucleus, as demonstrated by the nuclear splice-modifying activity of Morpholinos observed after microinjection into the cytosol of cells.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] Different methods are used for delivery into embryos, into cultured cells or into adult animals.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] A microinjection apparatus is usually used for delivery into an embryo, with injections most commonly performed at the single-cell or few-cell stage; an alternative method for embryonic delivery is electroporation, which can deliver oligos into tissues of later embryonic stages.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] Delivery into adult tissues is usually difficult, though there are a few systems allowing useful uptake of unmodified Morpholino oligos (including uptake into muscle cells with Duchenne muscular dystrophy or the vascular endothelial cells stressed during balloon angioplasty).
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] Though they permeate through intercellular spaces in tissues effectively, unconjugated PMOs have limited distribution into the cytosol and nuclear spaces within healthy tissues following IV administration.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] An octa-guanidinium dendrimer attached to the end of a Morpholino can deliver the modified oligo (called a Vivo-Morpholino) from the blood to the cytosol.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/morpholino] Delivery-enabled Morpholinos, such as peptide conjugates and Vivo-Morpholinos, show promise as therapeutics for viral and genetic diseases.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/nusinersen] Since the condition it treats is so rare, nusinersen has so-called "orphan drug" designation in the United States and the European Union.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/nusinersen] The drug is used to treat spinal muscular atrophy associated with a mutation in the *SMN1* gene.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/nusinersen] It is administered directly to the central nervous system (CNS) using intrathecal injection.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/nusinersen] In clinical trials, the drug halted the disease progression.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/nusinersen] In around 60% of infants affected by type 1 spinal muscular atrophy, it improves motor function.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/nusinersen] People treated with nusinersen had an increased risk of upper and lower respiratory infections and congestion, ear infections, constipation, pulmonary aspiration, teething, and scoliosis.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/nusinersen] There is a risk that growth of infants and children might be stunted.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/nusinersen] In older clinical trial subjects, the most common adverse events were headache, back pain, and other adverse effects from the spinal injection, such as post-dural-puncture headache.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/nusinersen] Although not observed in the trial patients, a reduction in platelets as well as a risk of kidney damage are theoretical risks for antisense drugs and therefore platelets and kidney function should be monitored during treatment.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/nusinersen] In 2018, several cases of communicating hydrocephalus in children and adults treated with nusinersen emerged; it remains unclear whether this was drug related.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/nusinersen] Spinal muscular atrophy is caused by loss-of-function mutations in the *SMN1* gene which codes for survival motor neuron (SMN) protein.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/nusinersen] People survive owing to low amounts of the SMN protein produced from the *SMN2* gene.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/nusinersen] Nusinersen modulates alternative splicing of the *SMN2* gene, functionally converting it into *SMN1* gene, thus increasing the level of SMN protein in the CNS.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/nusinersen] The drug distributes to CNS and peripheral tissues.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/nusinersen] The half-life is estimated to be 135 to 177 days in cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) and 63 to 87 days in blood plasma.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/nusinersen] The drug is metabolized via exonuclease (3′- and 5′)-mediated hydrolysis and does not interact with CYP450 enzymes.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/nusinersen] The primary route of elimination is likely by urinary excretion for nusinersen and its metabolites.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/nusinersen] Nusinersen is an antisense oligonucleotide in which the 2'-hydroxy groups of the ribofuranosyl rings are replaced with 2'-*O*-2-methoxyethyl groups and the phosphate linkages are replaced with phosphorothioate linkages.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/nusinersen] Nusinersen was developed in a collaboration between Adrian Krainer at Cold Spring Harbor Laboratory and Ionis Pharmaceuticals (formerly called Isis Pharmaceuticals).
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/nusinersen] Initial work of target discovery of nusinersen was done by Ravindra N.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/nusinersen] Singh and co-workers at the University of Massachusetts Medical School funded by Cure SMA.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/nusinersen] The license to Biogen included licenses to intellectual property that Ionis had acquired from Cold Spring Harbor Laboratory and University of Massachusetts.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/nusinersen] In November 2016, the new drug application was accepted under the FDA's priority review process on the strength of the Phase III trial and the unmet need, and was also accepted for review at the European Medicines Agency (EMA) at that time.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/nusinersen] It was approved by the FDA in December 2016 and by EMA in May 2017 as the first drug to treat SMA.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/nusinersen] Subsequently, nusinersen was approved to treat SMA in Canada (July 2017), Japan (July 2017), Brazil (August 2017), Switzerland (September 2017), and China (February 2019).
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/nusinersen] In 2023, additional clinical trials continued to validate the efficacy of nusinersen, particularly emphasizing the benefits of early intervention.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/nusinersen] The trials demonstrated significant improvements in motor function and survival rates among infants with SMA Type 1, underscoring the importance of prompt treatment to achieve optimal clinical outcomes.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/nusinersen] Nusinersen list price in the USA is US$125,000 per injection which puts the treatment cost at US$750,000 in the first year and US$375,000 annually after that.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/nusinersen] According to *The New York Times*, this places nusinersen "among the most expensive drugs in the world".
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/nusinersen] In October 2017, the authorities in Denmark recommended nusinersen for use only in a small subset of people with SMA type 1 (young babies) and refused to offer it as a standard treatment for all other people with SMA quoting an "unreasonably high price" compared to the benefit.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/nusinersen] Norwegian authorities rejected the funding in October 2017 because the price of the medicine was "unethically high".
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/nusinersen] In February 2018, the funding was approved for people under 18 years old.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/nusinersen] In April 2023 funding was expanded to include adults.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/nusinersen] In August 2018, the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE), which weighs the cost-effectiveness of therapies for the NHS in England and Wales, recommended against offering nusinersen to people with SMA.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/nusinersen] Children with SMA type 1 were treated in the UK under a Biogen-funded expanded access programme; after enrolling 80 children, the scheme closed to new people in November 2018.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/nusinersen] In May 2019, however, NICE reversed its stance and announced its decision to recommend nusinersen for use across a wide spectrum of SMA for a 5-year period.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/nusinersen] Both the manufacturer and patient groups disputed the numbers and pointed out that actual pricing arrangements for Ireland are in line with the negotiated price for the BeneluxA initiative which Ireland has been a member of since June 2018.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/nusinersen] As of May 2019, nusinersen was available in public healthcare in more than 40 countries.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/nusinersen] In December 2021, nusinersen was included in the extended insurance coverage of China, and the price was reduced from ¥697,000 per vial to around ¥33,000 (~US$5,100) per vial.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] Oligonucleotides are characterized by the sequence of nucleotide residues that make up the entire molecule.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] The length of the oligonucleotide is usually denoted by "-mer" (from Greek *meros*, "part").
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] For example, an oligonucleotide of six nucleotides (nt) is a hexamer, while one of 25 nt would usually be called a "25-mer".
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] Oligonucleotides readily bind, in a sequence-specific manner, to their respective complementary oligonucleotides, DNA, or RNA to form duplexes or, less often, hybrids of a higher order.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] This basic property serves as a foundation for the use of oligonucleotides as probes for detecting specific sequences of DNA or RNA.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] Examples of procedures that use oligonucleotides include DNA microarrays, Southern blots, ASO analysis, fluorescent in situ hybridization (FISH), PCR, and the synthesis of artificial genes.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] Oligonucleotides are composed of 2'-deoxyribonucleotides (oligodeoxyribonucleotides), which can be modified at the backbone or on the 2' sugar position to achieve different pharmacological effects.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] These modifications give new properties to the oligonucleotides and make them a key element in antisense therapy.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] Oligonucleotides are chemically synthesized using building blocks, protected phosphoramidites of natural or chemically modified nucleosides or, to a lesser extent, of non-nucleosidic compounds.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] The oligonucleotide chain assembly proceeds in the 3' to 5' direction by following a routine procedure referred to as a "synthetic cycle".
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] Completion of a single synthetic cycle results in the addition of one nucleotide residue to the growing chain.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] A less than 100% yield of each synthetic step and the occurrence of side reactions set practical limits of the efficiency of the process.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] In general, oligonucleotide sequences are usually short (13–25 nucleotides long).
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] The maximum length of synthetic oligonucleotides hardly exceeds 200 nucleotide residues.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] HPLC and other methods can be used to isolate products with the desired sequence.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] Creating chemically stable short oligonucleotides was the earliest challenge in developing ASO therapies.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] Naturally occurring oligonucleotides are easily degraded by nucleases, an enzyme that cleaves nucleotides and is ample in every cell type.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] Short oligonucleotide sequences also have weak intrinsic binding affinities, which contributes to their degradation in vivo.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] Nucleoside organothiophosphate (PS) analogs of nucleotides give oligonucleotides some beneficial properties.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] Key beneficial properties that PS backbones give nucleotides are diastereomer identification of each nucleotide and the ability to easily follow reactions involving the phosphorothioate nucleotides, which is useful in oligonucleotide synthesis.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] PS backbone modifications to oligonucleotides protects them against unwanted degradation by enzymes.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] Modifying the nucleotide backbone is widely used because it can be achieved with relative ease and accuracy on most nucleotides.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] Fluorescent modifications on 5' and 3' end of oligonucleotides was reported to evaluate the oligonucleotides structures, dynamics and interactions with respect to environment.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] Another modification that is useful for medical applications of oligonucleotides is 2' sugar modifications.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] Modifying the 2' position sugar increases the effectiveness of oligonucleotides by enhancing the target binding capabilities of oligonucleotides, specifically in antisense oligonucleotides therapies.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] They also decrease non specific protein binding, increasing the accuracy of targeting specific proteins.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] Two of the most commonly used modifications are 2'-O-methyl and the 2'-O-methoxyethyl.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] Fluorescent modifications on the nucleobase was also reported.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] Antisense oligonucleotides (ASO) are single strands of DNA or RNA that are complementary to a chosen sequence.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] In the case of antisense RNA they prevent protein translation of certain messenger RNA strands by binding to them, in a process called hybridization.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] Antisense oligonucleotides can be used to target a specific, complementary (coding or non-coding) RNA.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] If binding takes place this hybrid can be degraded by the enzyme RNase H.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] RNase H is an enzyme that hydrolyzes RNA, and when used in an antisense oligonucleotide application results in 80-95% down-regulation of mRNA expression.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] The use of Morpholino antisense oligonucleotides for gene knockdowns in vertebrates, which is now a standard technique in developmental biology and is used to study altered gene expression and gene function, was first developed by Janet Heasman using *Xenopus*.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] FDA-approved Morpholino drugs include eteplirsen and golodirsen.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] The antisense oligonucleotides have also been used to inhibit influenza virus replication in cell lines.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] Neurodegenerative diseases that are a result of a single mutant protein are good targets for antisense oligonucleotide therapies because of their ability to target and modify very specific sequences of RNA with high selectivity.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] Many genetic diseases including Huntington's disease, Alzheimer's disease, Parkinson's disease, and amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (ALS) have been linked to DNA alterations that result in incorrect RNA sequences and result in mistranslated proteins that have a toxic physiological effect.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] Cell uptake/internalisation still represents the biggest hurdle towards successful oligonucleotide (ON) therapeutics.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] A straightforward uptake, like for most small-molecule drugs, is hindered by the polyanionic backbone and the molecular size of ONs.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] The exact mechanisms of uptake and intracellular trafficking towards the place of action are still largely unclear.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] Moreover, small differences in ON structure/modification (vide supra) and difference in cell type leads to huge differences in uptake.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] It is believed that cell uptake occurs on different pathways after adsorption of ONs on the cell surface.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] Notably, studies show that most tissue culture cells readily take up ASOs (phosphorothiote linkage) in a non-productive way, meaning that no antisense effect is observed.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] In contrast to that conjugation of ASO with ligands recognised by G-coupled receptors leads to an increased productive uptake.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] Next to that classification (non-productive vs. productive), cell internalisation mostly proceeds in an energy-dependant way (receptor mediated endocytosis) but energy-independent passive diffusion (gymnosis) may not be ruled out.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] After passing the cell membrane, ON therapeutics are encapsulated in early endosomes which are transported towards late endosomes which are ultimately fused with lysosomes containing degrading enzymes at low pH.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] To exert its therapeutic function, the ON needs to escape the endosome prior to its degradation.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] Currently there is no universal method to overcome the problems of delivery, cell uptake and endosomal escape, but there exist several approaches which are tailored to specific cells and their receptors.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] A conjugation of ON therapeutics to an entity responsible for cell recognition/uptake not only increases the uptake (vide supra) but is also believed to decrease the complexity of the cell uptake as mainly one (ideally known) mechanism is then involved.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] This has been achieved with small molecule-ON conjugates for example bearing an N-acetyl galactosamine which targets receptors of hepatocytes.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] Another broadly used and heavily investigated entity for targeted delivery and increased cell uptake of oligonucleotides are antibodies.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] Alkylamides can be used as chromatographic stationary phases.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] Those phases have been investigated for the separation of oligonucleotides.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] Ion-pair reverse-phase high-performance liquid chromatography is used to separate and analyse the oligonucleotides after automated synthesis.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] A mixture of 5-methoxysalicylic acid and spermine can be used as a matrix for oligonucleotides analysis in MALDI mass spectrometry.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] ElectroSpray Ionization Mass Spectrometry (ESI-MS) is also a powerful tool to characterize the mass of oligonucleotides.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] DNA microarrays are a useful analytical application of oligonucleotides.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] Compared to standard cDNA microarrays, oligonucleotide based microarrays have more controlled specificity over hybridization, and the ability to measure the presence and prevalence of alternatively spliced or polyadenylated sequences.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] One subtype of DNA microarrays can be described as substrates (nylon, glass, etc.) to which oligonucleotides have been bound at high density.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/oligonucleotide] There are a number of applications of DNA microarrays within the life sciences.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/phosphorothioate] Oligonucleotide phosphorothioates (OPS) are modified oligonucleotides where one of the oxygen atoms in the phosphate moiety is replaced by sulfur.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/phosphorothioate] These compounds are the basis of antisense therapy, e.g., the drugs fomivirsen (Vitravene), oblimersen, alicaforsen, and mipomersen (Kynamro).
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/phosphorothioate] Variants with P=S double bonds were developed as insecticides because of their reduced mammalian toxicity.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/phosphorothioate] The phosphorothioate P=S bond is converted to the toxic P=O bond in the target insect.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/phosphorothioate] Similar oxidative conversion in mammals is slower, conferring lower toxicity in mammals.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/phosphorothioate] Generally these compounds feature tetrahedral phosphorus(V) centers.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/phosphorothioate] Classically, thiophosphates would include a P+-S− dative bond as illustrated by malathion.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/phosphorothioate] The terminology is used loosely and thiophosphates include P-S single bonds as illustrated by the drug amifostine.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/phosphorothioate] Dithiophosphonic anhydrides commonly form four-membered rings.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/phosphorothioate] They react with dienes in a hetero-Diels-Alder reaction.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/phosphorothioate] P–S single bonds can be generated through a variety of approaches, starting from thiols, disulfides, sulfinic acids as sulfur sources and various P(III) and P(V) coupling partners.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/phosphorothioate] PS–C bonds can also be formed through many comparable approaches, usually by alkylating a free phosphorus-thioate anion or thioic acid.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/phosphorothioate] Organothiophosphates are conceptually derived from the inorganic thiophosphates (PO4−*x*S3− *x*).
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/phosphorothioate] Dimethyl dithiophosphoric acid and diethyl dithiophosphoric acid are obtained in this way.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] The family is divided into evolutionarily related groups with slightly different substrate preferences, broadly designated ribonuclease H1 and H2.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] The human genome encodes both H1 and H2.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] Human ribonuclease H2 is a heterotrimeric complex composed of three subunits, mutations in any of which are among the genetic causes of a rare disease known as Aicardi–Goutières syndrome.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] A third type, closely related to H2, is found only in a few prokaryotes, whereas H1 and H2 occur in all domains of life.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] Additionally, RNase H1-like retroviral ribonuclease H domains occur in multidomain reverse transcriptase proteins, which are encoded by retroviruses such as HIV and are required for viral replication.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] In eukaryotes, ribonuclease H1 is involved in DNA replication of the mitochondrial genome.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] Both H1 and H2 are involved in genome maintenance tasks such as processing of R-loop structures.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] Ribonuclease H is a family of endonuclease enzymes with a shared substrate specificity for the RNA strand of RNA-DNA duplexes.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] By definition, RNases H cleave RNA backbone phosphodiester bonds to leave a 3' hydroxyl and a 5' phosphate group.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] RNases H can be broadly divided into two subtypes, H1 and H2, which for historical reasons are given Arabic numeral designations in eukaryotes and Roman numeral designations in prokaryotes.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] Thus the *Escherichia coli* RNase HI is a homolog of the *Homo sapiens* RNase H1.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] In *E. coli* and many other prokaryotes, the *rnhA* gene encodes HI and the *rnhB* gene encodes HII.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] A third related class, called HIII, occurs in a few bacteria and archaea; it is closely related to prokaryotic HII enzymes.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] The structure of RNase H commonly consists of a 5-stranded β-sheet surrounded by a distribution of α-helices.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] All RNases H have an active site centered on a conserved sequence motif composed of aspartate and glutamate residues, often referred to as the DEDD motif.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] These residues interact with catalytically required magnesium ions.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] RNases H2 are larger than H1 and usually have additional helices.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] The domain organization of the enzymes varies; some prokaryotic and most eukaryotic members of the H1 group have an additional small domain at the N-terminus known as the "hybrid binding domain", which facilitates binding to RNA:DNA hybrid duplexes and sometimes confers increased processivity.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] While all members of the H1 group and the prokaryotic members of the H2 group function as monomers, eukaryotic H2 enzymes are obligate heterotrimers.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] Prokaryotic HIII enzymes are members of the broader H2 group and share most structural features with H2, with the addition of an N-terminal TATA box binding domain.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] Retroviral RNase H domains occurring in multidomain reverse transcriptase proteins have structures closely resembling the H1 group.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] RNases H1 have been extensively studied to explore the relationships between structure and enzymatic activity.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] They are also used, especially the *E. coli* homolog, as model systems to study protein folding.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] Within the H1 group, a relationship has been identified between higher substrate-binding affinity and the presence of structural elements consisting of a helix and flexible loop providing a larger and more basic substrate-binding surface.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] The C-helix has a scattered taxonomic distribution; it is present in the *E. coli* and human RNase H1 homologs and absent in the HIV RNase H domain, but examples of retroviral domains with C-helices do exist.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] Depending on the differences in their amino acid sequences, these RNases H are classified into type 1 and type 2 RNases H.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] Type 1 RNases H have prokaryotic and eukaryotic RNases H1 and retroviral RNase H.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] Type 2 RNases H have prokaryotic and eukaryotic RNases H2 and bacterial RNase H3.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] These RNases H exist in a monomeric form, except for eukaryotic RNases H2, which exist in a heterotrimeric form.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] RNase H1 and H2 have distinct substrate preferences and distinct but overlapping functions in the cell.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] In prokaryotes and lower eukaryotes, neither enzyme is essential, whereas both are believed to be essential in higher eukaryotes.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] The combined activity of both H1 and H2 enzymes is associated with maintenance of genome stability due to the enzymes' degradation of the RNA component of R-loops.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] Ribonuclease H1 enzymes require at least four ribonucleotide-containing base pairs in a substrate and cannot remove a single ribonucleotide from a strand that is otherwise composed of deoxyribonucleotides.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] For this reason, it is considered unlikely that RNase H1 enzymes are involved in the processing of RNA primers from Okazaki fragments during DNA replication.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] RNase H1 is not essential in unicellular organisms where it has been investigated; in *E. coli*, RNase H1 knockouts confer a temperature-sensitive phenotype, and in *S. cerevisiae*, they produce defects in stress response.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] In many eukaryotes, including mammals, RNase H1 genes include a mitochondrial targeting sequence, leading to expression of isoforms with and without the MTS present.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] As a result, RNase H1 is localized to both mitochondria and the nucleus.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] In knockout mouse models, RNase H1-null mutants are lethal during embryogenesis due to defects in replicating mitochondrial DNA.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] The defects in mitochondrial DNA replication induced by loss of RNase H1 are likely due to defects in R-loop processing.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] In prokaryotes, RNase H2 is enzymatically active as a monomeric protein.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] In eukaryotes, it is an obligate heterotrimer composed of a catalytic subunit A and structural subunits B and C.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] While the A subunit is closely homologous to the prokaryotic RNase H2, the B and C subunits have no apparent homologs in prokaryotes and are poorly conserved at the sequence level even among eukaryotes.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] The B subunit mediates protein-protein interactions between the H2 complex and PCNA, which localizes H2 to replication foci.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] The substrate specificity of RNase H2 gives it a role in ribonucleotide excision repair, removing misincorporated ribonucleotides from DNA, in addition to R-loop processing.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] Although both H1 and H2 are present in the mammalian cell nucleus, H2 is the dominant source of RNase H activity there and is important for maintaining genome stability.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] Some prokaryotes possess an additional H2-type gene designated RNase HIII in the Roman-numeral nomenclature used for the prokaryotic genes.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] HIII proteins are more closely related to the H2 group by sequence identity and structural similarity, but have substrate preferences that more closely resemble H1.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] Unlike HI and HII, which are both widely distributed among prokaryotes, HIII is found in only a few organisms with a scattered taxonomic distribution; it is somewhat more common in archaea and is rarely or never found in the same prokaryotic genome as HI.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] The active site of nearly all RNases H contains four negatively charged amino acid residues, known as the DEDD motif; often a histidine is also present (e.g. in HIV-1, human or E. coli).
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] The charged residues bind two metal ions that are required for catalysis; under physiological conditions these are magnesium ions, but manganese also usually supports enzymatic activity, while calcium or high concentration of Mg2+ inhibits activity.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] Based on experimental evidence and computer simulations the enzyme activates a water molecule bound to one of the metal ions with the conserved histidine.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] The transition state is associative in nature and forms an intermediate with protonated phosphate and deprotonated alkoxide leaving group.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] The leaving group is protonated via the glutamate which has an elevated pKa and is likely to be protonated.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] The mechanism is similar to RNase T and the RuvC subunit in the Cas9 enzyme which both also use a histidine and a two-metal ion mechanism.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] The mechanism of the release of the cleaved product is still unresolved.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] Experimental evidence from time-resolved crystallography and similar nucleases points to a role of a third ion in the reaction recruited to the active site.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] In addition, genetic material of retroviral origin appears frequently in the genome, reflecting integration of the genomes of human endogenous retroviruses.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] Such integration events result in the presence of genes encoding retroviral reverse transcriptase, which includes an RNase H domain.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] Long terminal repeat (LTR) and non-long terminal repeat (non-LTR) retrotransposons are also common in the genome and often include their own RNase H domains, with a complex evolutionary history.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] In small studies, mutations in human RNase H1 have been associated with chronic progressive external ophthalmoplegia, a common feature of mitochondrial disease.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] Mutations in any of the three RNase H2 subunits are well-established as causes of a rare genetic disorder known as Aicardi–Goutières syndrome (AGS), which manifests as neurological and dermatological symptoms at an early age.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] The symptoms of AGS closely resemble those of congenital viral infection and are associated with inappropriate upregulation of type I interferon.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] AGS can also be caused by mutations in other genes: TREX1, SAMHD1, ADAR, and MDA5/IFIH1, all of which are involved in nucleic acid processing.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] Characterization of mutational distribution in an AGS patient population found 5% of all AGS mutations in RNASEH2A, 36% in 2B, and 12% in 2C.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] Mutations in 2B have been associated with somewhat milder neurological impairment and with an absence of interferon-induced gene upregulation that can be detected in patients with other AGS-associated genotypes.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] Pathogenic examples include human immunodeficiency virus and hepatitis B virus, respectively.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] Both encode large multifunctional reverse transcriptase (RT) proteins containing RNase H domains.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] Retroviral RT proteins from HIV-1 and murine leukemia virus are the best-studied members of the family.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] Retroviral RT is responsible for converting the virus' single-stranded RNA genome into double-stranded DNA.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] The second step of this process is carried out by an RNase H domain located at the C-terminus of the RT protein.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] RNase H performs three types of cleaving actions: non-specific degradation of the plus-strand RNA genome, specific removal of the minus-strand tRNA primer, and removal of the plus-strand purine-rich polypurine tract (PPT) primer.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] RNase H plays a role in the priming of the plus-strand, but not in the conventional method of synthesizing a new primer sequence.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] Rather RNase H creates a "primer" from the PPT that is resistant to RNase H cleavage.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] By removing all bases but the PPT, the PPT is used as a marker for the end of the U3 region of its long terminal repeat.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] Because RNase H activity is required for viral proliferation, this domain has been considered a drug target for the development of antiretroviral drugs used in the treatment of HIV/AIDS and other conditions caused by retroviruses.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] Inhibitors of retroviral RNase H of several different chemotypes have been identified, many of which have a mechanism of action based on chelation of the active-site cations.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] Reverse-transcriptase inhibitors that specifically inhibit the polymerase function of RT are in widespread clinical use, but not inhibitors of the RNase H function; it is the only enzymatic function encoded by HIV that is not yet targeted by drugs in clinical use.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] RNases H are widely distributed and occur in all domains of life.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] The family belongs to a larger superfamily of nuclease enzymes and is considered to be evolutionarily ancient.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] In prokaryotic genomes, multiple RNase H genes are often present, but there is little correlation between occurrence of HI, HII, and HIII genes and overall phylogenetic relationships, suggesting that horizontal gene transfer may have played a role in establishing the distribution of these enzymes.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] RNase HI and HIII rarely or never appear in the same prokaryotic genome.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] When an organism's genome contains more than one RNase H gene, they sometimes have significant differences in activity level.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] These observations have been suggested to reflect an evolutionary pattern that minimizes functional redundancy among RNase H genes.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] RNase HIII, which is unique to prokaryotes, has a scattered taxonomic distribution and is found in both bacteria and archaea; it is believed to have diverged from HII fairly early.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] The evolutionary trajectory of RNase H2 in eukaryotes, especially the mechanism by which eukaryotic homologs became obligate heterotrimers, is unclear; the B and C subunits have no apparent homologs in prokaryotes.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] Because RNase H specifically degrades only the RNA in double-stranded RNA:DNA hybrids, it is commonly used as a laboratory reagent in molecular biology.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] Purified preparations of *E. coli* RNase HI and HII are commercially available.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] RNase HI is often used to destroy the RNA template after first-strand complementary DNA (cDNA) synthesis by reverse transcription.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] It can also be used to cleave specific RNA sequences in the presence of short complementary segments of DNA.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] Highly sensitive techniques such as surface plasmon resonance can be used for detection.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] RNase HII can be used to degrade the RNA primer component of an Okazaki fragment or to introduce single-stranded nicks at positions containing a ribonucleotide.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] A variant of hot start PCR, known as RNase H-dependent PCR or rhPCR, has been described using a thermostable RNase HII from the hyperthermophilic archaeon *Pyrococcus abyssi*.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] Of note, the ribonuclease inhibitor protein commonly used as a reagent is not effective at inhibiting the activity of either HI or HII.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] Ribonucleases H were first discovered in the laboratory of Peter Hausen when researchers found RNA:DNA hybrid endonuclease activity in calf thymus in 1969 and gave it the name "ribonuclease *H*" to designate its *hybrid* specificity.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] RNase H activity was subsequently discovered in *E. coli* and in a sample of oncoviruses with RNA genomes during early studies of viral reverse transcription.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] It later became clear that calf thymus extract contained more than one protein with RNase H activity and that *E. coli* contained two RNase H genes.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] The prokaryotic RNase HIII, reported in 1999, was the last RNase H subtype to be identified.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] Characterizing eukaryotic RNase H2 was historically a challenge, in part due to its low abundance.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] Careful efforts at purification of the enzyme suggested that, unlike the *E. coli* RNase H2, the eukaryotic enzyme had multiple subunits.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] The *S. cerevisiae* homolog of the *E. coli* protein (that is, the H2A subunit) was easily identifiable by bioinformatics when the yeast genome was sequenced, but the corresponding protein was found not to have enzymatic activity in isolation.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] Eventually, the yeast B and C subunits were isolated by co-purification and found to be required for enzymatic activity.
[src:antisense-oligonucleotides/rnase-h] However, the yeast B and C subunits have very low sequence identity to their homologs in other organisms, and the corresponding human proteins were conclusively identified only after mutations in all three were found to cause Aicardi–Goutières syndrome.
